    "narrative": "Our offensive outlook for April 30th is defined by the \"sprint speed premium,\" as we lean into matchups that offer high stolen base potential against pitchers with slower deliveries. **Vinnie Pasquantino** leads our daily efficiency scores at 61.54, capitalizing on a favorable matchup against Jeffrey Springs. While the platoon disadvantage against a lefty limits his ceiling, the weak 4.60 xERA of the opposing starter provides enough cushion for him to anchor the lineup. We are also closely monitoring **Tyler Soderstrom**, whose 59.66 rating is bolstered by a significant park factor, making him a high-upside play despite the looming concerns of a projected lefty-lefty matchup. **Corbin Carroll** remains a core start (59.06); although he faces the elite command of Brandon Woodruff, his 100% stolen base opportunity score against a slow-working delivery makes him indispensable for our pursuit of the SB category.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the card was between **Brice Turang** and **James Wood**, both of whom hover near the 56-58 range. While **Brice Turang** (58.33) edged out the final start due to a favorable matchup against Michael Soroka, we are keeping a close eye on **James Wood** (56.01). **James Wood** was the closest player to being benched, ultimately getting the nod over the likes of **Mickey Moniak** (48.06) because of the sheer volume of base-path opportunities expected when leading off against Freddy Peralta. **Mickey Moniak** suffers from the most severe platoon drag of the day (-15%), which ultimately dropped him below our preferred threshold. We remain cautious regarding all projections until official lineups are posted, as the potential for defensive shuffling could volatility-adjust these scores downward. With **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Jose Caballero**, **Josh Naylor**, and **Trevor Story** all sidelined by scheduled off-days, we are relying on our depth players like **Austin Riley** (51.50) to mitigate the lack of bench reinforcements.",
